summary.seg: Emmanuel College, MS 15 was probably copied in the 11th or 12th century, and is the second volume of a set of two (the first being Emmanuel MS 14). It contains 22 homilies by the Patriarch of Constantinople, John Chrysostom, In Matthaeum homiliae (68-90) (Emmanuel MS 14 contains homilies 48-68). Emmanuel MSS 12-15, which all contain copies of Chrysostom's homilies on the Gospel of Matthew, share a common provenance and history, and were used by Frederick Field for his edition of the homilies (Cambridge 1839; see vol. 1, p. XVIII and XXI).

collation.p: The manuscript consists of 18 quires, all quaternia.

list.item: Quire 78-3 ff. 193-[197] The fourth, fifth and eighth folios have been lost, with loss of text.
Quire 148-1 ff. 246-[252] The second folio has been lost, with loss of text.
Quires 16-178 ff. 259-[274] The fourth and fifth folios have been lost, with loss of text.
Quire 188-7 f. 275 A single folio of this quire survives, not continuous with the preceding one.

signatures.p: Signatures in Greek numerals, continuing from Emmanuel MS 14, in brown ink on first recto, lower internal corner, on quires 1-12 (from f. 145r to f. 230r) κβʹ to λγʹ, and on quire 17 (f. 267r), ληʹ.
Later signatures in Arabic numerals, continuing from Emmanuel MS 14, in light-brown ink on external margins of first recto and last verso from quire 1, numbered 7-23 from f. 145r.
Modern signatures in Greek numerals in pencil on first recto of quires 13-17 from λδʹ to ληʹ from f. 238r to f. 267r, suppling missing signatures.

supportDesc.condition: Most of f. [272] has been torn away, as has much of the lower part of f. 275, with some loss of text. The outer margin of f. [195] has been cut away, with slight loss of text. There are tears along the ruling in ff. [160], [173] and [202], which have been repaired with Japanese paper. Small holes appear in some folios (e.g. ff. [274]-275), some of which have been repaired with Japanese paper. There is some cockling and creasing, including pleating to f. 145. There is some water staining, drops of wax and areas of dirt. Red paint has marked ff. 267v-[268]r.

layoutDesc.layout:
Two columns of 33 lines. 257 175
Pricking survives in the upper and lowre margins, but much has been lost to cropping. Ruled in hardpoint, system Leroy 1, type Leroy 44C2. Text hangs from the lines.

handNote.p: The manuscript is written in a mixed minuscule script, by the same hand as Emmanuel MS 14.

decoDesc.decoNote: Headpiece outlined in red ink on f. 15v.
Initials in red ink for each homily.

additions.p: A notes on f. [iii] verso: A reference to the edition by Henry Savile, Sancti Ioannis Chrysostomi opera Graece, Eton College, 1612-13: Vide Editionem Savili Etonae impressam Anno MDCXII. Vol. 2. p. 434. l. 20. καὶ οὕτως ἐμπρησθεὶς κ.τ.λ.

binding.p: 18th-century full leather binding over millboards, sewn with cord on single raised supports, boards attached with laced-in slips Separate-sewn endbands, the outermost and the pastedowns of marbled paper. Hatched leather on the boards, with decorative gold tooling on boards and spine. The title Chrysosto Homiliae Vol. IV. MS is tooled in gold on black labels on the spine, and the classmark appears on patches.
binding.condition: The left outer joint is mostly split at the tail and both endcaps are damaged. The leather covering has become flaky.

history.origin: The manuscript was copied in in the 11th or 12th century.
history.provenance:
As Emmanuel MS 14, the manuscript comes from the Monastery of Kastamoniti of Mount Athos. The manuscript was bought by
Anthony Askew (1722-1774) Askew, Anthony, 1722-1774, physician and book collector, in his travel to the Mt Athos. After his death, the manuscripts were sold by G. Leigh and J. Sotheby in the auction of his library in 1785 (Lot. n. 612), but his son
Adam Askew (1752-1844) Askew, Adam 1752-1844 was able to get possession of them again and gave them to
Samuel Parr (1747-1825) Parr, Samuel, 1747-1825 and eventually presented by him to Emmanuel College in 1814, as in the note on f. [iii] verso.

acquisition.p: Eventually presented to Emmanuel College by Samuel Parr in 1814.

recordHist.source: Description (2021) draws on M.R. James, The Western manuscripts in the library of Emmanuel College: a descriptive catalogue, Cambridge University Press, Cambridge, 1904, p. 12-13.
